-- Hang Seng Index Rises to 11-Month High on Policy Speculation; HSBC Gains
-- B y   J o n a t h a n   B u r g o s
-- 2010-10-06T08:46:59Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-06/hang-seng-index-rises-to-11-month-high-on-policy-speculation-hsbc-gains.html
Hong Kong  stocks  rose, driving the
Hang Seng Index to an 11-month high, on speculation more central
banks will act to spur economic growth after the Bank of Japan
cut its benchmark interest rate yesterday.  HSBC Holdings Plc , Europe’s biggest lender, climbed 1.4
percent ahead of a Bank of England meeting tomorrow to review
monetary policy.  Esprit Holdings Ltd. , which gets 85 percent of
sales from Europe, gained 2.6 percent.  New World Development Co. ,
the Hong Kong developer controlled by billionaire  Cheng Yu-tung ,
advanced 4.9 percent after reporting full-year earnings jumped
more than five times.  “We can increase weights on risk assets,” said  Pu Yonghao ,
Hong Kong-based chief investment strategist for the Asia-Pacific
at UBS Wealth Management, which has assets of $190 billion.
Given prospects of further quantitative easing, the global
economy “can avoid a double-dip scenario,” he told Bloomberg
Television.  The  Hang Seng Index  advanced 1.1 percent to 22,880.41 as of
the 4:00 p.m. close in Hong Kong, the highest closing level
since Nov. 17, 2009. Three stocks rose for each one that fell on
the 45-member gauge.  The benchmark index surged 11 percent in the quarter ended
Sept. 30 as corporate earnings and economic reports boosted
confidence the global recovery will not falter. That’s the
biggest quarterly increase from the same period a year earlier.
Stocks in the measure trade at an average 14.7 times  estimated
earnings , the highest level since January.  ‘Monetary Easing’  The  Hang Seng China Enterprises Index  of so-called H shares
of Chinese companies rose 0.7 percent to 12,772.03. Mainland
Chinese markets are shut for holidays and are due to resume
trading on Oct. 8.  Speculation that central banks will step up measures to
bolster their economies grew after the Bank of Japan yesterday
cut its benchmark overnight interest rate target to a range of
zero to 0.1 percent, the lowest level since 2006, from 0.1
percent. Policy makers will set up a 5 trillion yen ($60 billion)
fund to buy government bonds and other assets, inflating the
balance sheet as U.S. and U.K. central bankers contemplate
similar moves.  HSBC gained 1.4 percent to HK$82.05. The Bank of England
will probably keep its stimulus program at the current level of
200 billion pounds ($318 billion) to aid economic growth when
policy makers meet tomorrow.  The BOE will leave the value of their bond holdings
unchanged, according to the median forecast of 36 economists
surveyed by Bloomberg News. The bank will also maintain its
benchmark interest rate at a record low of 0.5 percent, all 60
economists in a separate survey said.  Biggest Market  Financial stocks accounted for 47 percent of the Hang Seng
Index’s advance. Industrial & Commercial Bank of China Ltd., the
nation’s biggest lender, rose 1.9 percent to HK$5.89.  China
Construction Bank Corp. , the No. 2, jumped 1.8 percent to
HK$6.91. Bank of China Ltd., the third-largest, advanced 2.9
percent to HK$4.28.  Esprit Holdings, the Hong Kong-based clothier that counts
Europe as its biggest export market, climbed 2.6 percent to
HK$42.95.  Cosco Pacific Ltd. , which runs some terminal
operations at Greece’s largest shipping port, rose 2.7 percent
to HK$12.20.  Shares of raw material suppliers gained after crude oil and
metal prices increased yesterday. Crude oil for November
delivery jumped 1.7 percent in New York to the highest close
since May 3. The  London Metals Index , which tracks prices of six
metals including aluminum and copper, gained 1.6 percent.  Cnooc Ltd. , China’s biggest offshore explorer of oil and
gas, gained 2.5 percent to HK$16.30. Aluminum Corp. of China
Ltd., the largest Chinese producer of the metal, increased 1.4
percent to HK$7.68.  New World  New World Development gained 4.9 percent to HK$16.70. The
company said full-year net income increased to HK$11.6 billion
($1.5 billion) from HK$2.08 billion a year earlier as rental
income and apartment sales climbed.  Hang Lung Properties Ltd. , Hong Kong’s third-biggest
homebuilder, surged 4.6 percent to HK$38.45, its highest closing
level since October 2007. Cheung Kong Holdings Ltd., the city’s
second-biggest developer, rose 1.4 percent to HK$116.90. Sun
Hung Kai Properties Ltd., the world’s biggest developer,
increased 1.2 percent to HK$134.10.  China Mobile Ltd. , the world’s biggest phone carrier,
gained 1.7 percent to HK$81.85. BNP Paribas initiated coverage
of the stock with a “buy” rating, saying it is the brokerage’s
top pick among Chinese telecommunications companies.  Among stocks that declined,  China Everbright Ltd. , a
government investment company, fell 3.1 percent to HK$18.78. The
company said its controlling shareholder, Honorich Holdings Ltd.,
sold 129 million shares at HK$18 each.  Futures on the Hang Seng Index rose 1 percent to 22,920.  To contact the reporter on this story:
 Jonathan Burgos  in Singapore at 
